<h1 style="font-size: 250%; text-align: left; margin-bottom: 20px">Mismeasurement & Missingness</h1>
<img src="./resources/images/intro_dag_full.png" style="position: absolute; left: 15%; top: 37%; width: 80%; opacity: .4; filter: blur(1px)"/>
<br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br>
<span class="today large" style="margin-bottom: 20px"></span><br>
.large[Dean Knox] &nbsp; .small.highlight[**Wharton**]

???
- Thanks, xxx. Glad to be here.
- I'm going to be talking about the oversight and reform of police agencies
- and the challenges posed by police records, which are a problematic data source
- I'll show that we need to be very careful in analyzing this data, given all
  the things they **don't** see about police-civilian interactions
- and I'll provide some computational algorithms that can help us think through
  the implications of these data imperfections for the conclusions we can draw

---

# Police oversight: a review

???
- You probably don't need me to tell you why this is important
- But I do want to make two broad points to put things in context
- First
  - Police agencies are one of the most common public organizations around
  - I'd guess that almost everyone here has interacted with an officer at some point
- And second, police agencies suffer from a lack of perceived legitimacy
  - This isn't new, but it's worse than ever, at least in the 30 years Gallup's been tracking
  - and more specifically, two-thirds of Americans see police as discriminatory,
    trigger-happy, and unaccountable for their actions

--
- Among the most ubiquitous public organizations
  - Over 18k local law-enforcement agencies across US
  - Police contact >20% of Americans each year .tiny[(BJS, '22)]

--
- Confidence in police at a historic low: 43% .tiny[(Gallup, '23)]
  
--
  - Treating racial and ethnic groups equally: 65% negative .tiny[(Pew, '20)]
  - Using the right amount of force: 64% negative .tiny[(Pew, '20)]

--
- Police misconduct remains disturbingly frequent

???
- And this isn't just an LAPD issue
- In the last few years alone, we've seen the killing of Breonna Taylor, the murders of George Floyd and Tyre Nichols, and too many others

---

