# Police oversight: a review

- Among the most ubiquitous public organizations
  - Over 18k local law-enforcement agencies across US
  - Police contact >20% of Americans each year .tiny[(BJS, '22)]
- Confidence in police at a historic low: 43% .tiny[(Gallup, '23)]
  - Treating racial and ethnic groups equally: 65% negative .tiny[(Pew, '20)]
  - Using the right amount of force: 64% negative .tiny[(Pew, '20)]
- Police misconduct remains disturbingly frequent
  - Breonna Taylor killing, George Floyd & Tyre Nichols murders

???
- I should say that these aren't just sensationalist examples
- these are all cases where, as part of the DOJ investigation team,
  we're implementing exactly the concepts that I'll describe
- Now, police agencies have strong incentives to address these issues themselves
  - It's well known that when people see the police as legitimate
  - They're more willing to report crimes and provide evidence
- But for a variety of reasons, historically, reform just hasn't come from within
  - these include the strength of unions and the "thin blue line" culture
- instead, reform tends to come from external sources, especially lawsuits and
  federal investigations
  - and that means it's crucial to statistically estimate misconduct and
    understand where it's coming from
  - because you can't reform what you can't see

--
- Undermines org. performance .tiny[(Obama Task Force on Policing, '15)]
  - Public trust & legitimacy &rightarrow; obey law, help investigations

--
- Cultural & institutional barriers to internal reform
  - Reform comes from courts, fed. investigations, legislation

--
  - This means quantifying misconduct is prerequisite to reform



---

# The central challenge

- Classic principal-agent problem:
  - Democratically elected principals seek to uphold civil rights
  - Agents seek to preserve discretion, resist civilian oversight

???
- At this point, you're probably thinking this sounds like a classic
  principal-agent problem, and you'd be right
  - The general public, through democratically elected leaders,
    delegate the power to legally use force to police agents so they can enforce
    the law
  - And the goal of civilian oversight is to ensure that agents do that while
    upholding civil rights
- This is one of the hardest principal-agent problems imaginable
  - and even apart from the public-policy issues, these least-likely case are
    worth studying
  - because there are all kinds of interesting challenges, and resolving them
    leads to some very interesting new theory
- Here's the central problem:
  - Almost all the data that we use for oversight is self-reported, through
    organizational processes designed by police, for police purposes
- and the core point I want to make, the one thing I hope you take away from
  this talk
- Is that for this reason, we can't simply apply off-the-shelf methods designed
  for as-if-randomly sampled, gold-standard data
  - I'll show you that when we do that, we draw unsupportable conclusions
  - and instead, we have to account for the processes that filter and distort
    what we get to see

--
- Monitoring relies heavily on agent self-reporting
  - Data has inaccuracies, selective reporting, omitted variables
.footnote[
<table style="left: 5%; width: 95%; font-size: 20px">
<col style="width: 5%">
<col style="width: 90%">
  <tr>
    <td align="center"><strong style="">[1]</strong></td>
    <td>Dean Knox. 2021. "Revealing racial bias: Causal inference can make
sense of imperfect policing data." <i>Science</i>.</td>
  </tr>
</table>
]

--
- Incomplete data undermines oversight & monitoring
  - Off-the-shelf statistical methods &rightarrow; unsupportable claims
  - Must account for org. processes by which data are collected


<!-- -- -->
<!-- - Many claims can be consistent with incomplete data -->
<!--   - High-stakes settings require maximally cautious inferences -->

---

# Overview

1. Fundamental limits of policing data & analyses
  - What we can & cannot see about agent behavior
  - Desire for "the answer" &rightarrow; unsupported conclusions

???
- In the rest of this talk, I'm first going to clarify exactly what I mean when
  I say "police data is incomplete"
  - I'll show that it just doesn't make sense to think about "the answer" to a
    question like "how much do police discriminate?" given those
    challenges. there are many possible answers, all of which are consistent
    with the available information
- that's going to bring us to the focus of today's talk, which is the following
  very general question: suppose you have some social process you want to study,
  and some incomplete data about it. what's the **range** of possible answers?
  - this is going to have the flavor of formal logic: here are the theoretical
    premises, here is the data we've been able to collect. I'll argue that we,
    as scientists, should be spending our time here
  - but then, given that, we should ask: what are the scientific conclusions
    that follow? and I'll argue that computers should handle this tedious
    deduction
- I'll show how this can help us reason about police oversight by asking, what's
  the best case? is it possible that officers are enforcing the law in a
  race-neutral manner? if not, what's the worse case? how bad could it be?
- and I'll show that we can think about how to design work so that we limit the
  worst-case harm that agents can cause
- finally, I'll show you how similar challenges arise all the time in social
  science, with examples from another famous discrimination case (Walmart v
  Dukes), with examples of descriptive research (drawing on some of my own work
  using computational proxies, like estimates of vocal tone and facial
  expressions, to study conversation). 


--
1. Algorithm-assisted deduction from theory & evidence
  - Given explicit theoretical premises & incomplete data,<br>

--
    what is the range of conclusions that can be drawn?
--
  - Quantifying best-case racial discrimination in policing

--
  - Org. design to limit worst-case harm from agent discretion

--
1. Broad applicability to other settings that require careful reasoning from
   theory & incomplete data

--
  - Other discrimination litigation, e.g. *Wal-Mart v. Dukes*

--
  - Descriptive research, e.g. conversation analysis w/ proxies

--
  - Causal research under selection, missingness, confounding...


---

class: center, middle, inverse

# Data limitations
# in police oversight

???
- so, let's dive right in
- I'll start by showing you what the data looks like
---

<img src="./resources/images/intro_dag_01.png" style="position: absolute; left: 2.5%; top: 20%; width: 100%; z-index: ;"/>
???
- one of the most important tasks in oversight is assessing racial bias in use of force
- here, our unit of analysis is the police-civilian encounter
- in this diagram, that means estimating whether force (the outcome) is used at
  different rates if, hypothetically, we could swap out a minority civilian for
  a white civilian in every encounter

---
<img src="./resources/images/intro_dag_02.png" style="position: absolute; left: 2.5%; top: 20%; width: 100%; z-index: ;"/>
???
- for this to be a useful exercise, we'll need to account for civilian behavior (for the sake of argument, let's say we swap in a white actor who is behaving the same way)
---
<img src="./resources/images/intro_dag_03.png" style="position: absolute; left: 2.5%; top: 20%; width: 100%; z-index: ;"/>
???
- we'll also need to consider context like the time of day, perhaps the officer's assigned job (like traffic enforcement or bike patrol)
- and after accounting for all this, we'll ask whether there's discriminatory violence
---
<img src="./resources/images/intro_dag_04.png" style="position: absolute; left: 2.5%; top: 20%; width: 100%; z-index: ;"/>
???
- it's important to note that officers rarely jump directly to force
- what usually happens is they detain a civilian, perhaps interrogate them,
  before escalating to violence
---
<img src="./resources/images/intro_dag_05.png" style="position: absolute; left: 2.5%; top: 20%; width: 100%; z-index: ;"/>
???
- and during the course of that stop, other events can be informative
- for example, if officers are looking for weapons, we can ask: how often were
  they found? if that differs by race, it can indicate there's discrimination in
  who officers are stopping
---
<img src="./resources/images/intro_dag_06.png" style="position: absolute; left: 2.5%; top: 20%; width: 100%; z-index: ;"/>
???
- OK, so one of the questions we'll look at today is diversity reforms in hiring
- this is a big proposal from the literature on bureaucracies (descriptive
  representation, to hire officers that look like they people they serve)
- and the question is whether those officers actually do their jobs differently,
  or if "blue is blue" and it doesn't matter
---
<img src="./resources/images/intro_dag_07.png" style="position: absolute; left: 2.5%; top: 20%; width: 100%; z-index: ;"/>
???
- the thing is, there are all kinds of other factors that influence an officer's decisions
- someone who's more suspicious, or even just feeling cranky that day, they may
  be more willing to initiate a stop and use force
---
<img src="./resources/images/intro_dag_08.png" style="position: absolute; left: 2.5%; top: 20%; width: 100%; z-index: ;"/>
???
- but that kind of information on an officer's mental state will never appear in
  administrative records
---
<img src="./resources/images/intro_dag_09.png" style="position: absolute; left: 2.5%; top: 20%; width: 100%; z-index: ;"/>
???
- and that's not the only problem
- in most cases, we don't get to see the actual behavior of the civilian
---
<img src="./resources/images/intro_dag_10.png" style="position: absolute; left: 2.5%; top: 20%; width: 100%; z-index: ;"/>
???
- we only get the description reported by the officer
---
<img src="./resources/images/intro_dag_11.png" style="position: absolute; left: 2.5%; top: 20%; width: 100%; z-index: ;"/>
???
- and what's more, we only see any of this if a stop is made, and officers fill out the stop form
---
<img src="./resources/images/intro_dag_12.png" style="position: absolute; left: 2.5%; top: 20%; width: 100%; z-index: ;"/>
???
- if they choose not to initiate that stop, then the encounter just vanishes
  without a trace in the data
---

class: center, middle, inverse

# Drawing inferences from
# incomplete police data:
# two motivating examples

???
- as you can see, things get complicated very fast
- so with that context, let's now consider how these issues affect the recent
  literature on policing

---

name: johnsonetal_hook

# Johnson et al. ('19),&ensp;.small[*PNAS*]
<img id="slidedownshrink" src="./resources/images/intro_dag_full.png" style="position: absolute; left: 2.5%; top: 20%; width: 100%; z-index: ;"/>
???
- johnson et al. was a PNAS study that had a major impact on the public discourse
- it was cited in congressional testimony and wall st journal op-eds
- at a high level, it made two claims
---
# Johnson et al. ('19),&ensp;.small[*PNAS*]
<img src="./resources/images/intro_dag_full.png" id="sliddownshrunk" style="position: absolute; left: 2.5%; top: 20%; width: 100%; z-index: ;"/>
