# Johnson et al. ('19),&ensp;.small[*PNAS*]
<p style="text-align: center; color: #A51C30;">"White officers are not more likely to shoot minority civilians than non-White officers... increasing diversity... is unlikely to reduce racial disparity in police shootings"</p>

<img src="./resources/images/johnsonetal_f0.png" id="sliddownshrunk" style="position: absolute; left: 2.5%; top: 20%; width: 100%; z-index: ;"/>
???
- the second claim was that diversifying police forces won't work

---

# How was the data analyzed?

???
- these are big claims that we'd hope are based on strong reasoning
  - because this stuff really matters
  - you may recall a headline from 2020, when a high-ranking major in the Tulsa
    PD reviewed the literature and said in an interview "all of their research
    says we're shooting African Americans... less than we probably ought to be"
  - He was referring to this paper and another one, by Roland Fryer, that I'll
    discuss in a second
- here's what I would've liked to see
  - define the monitoring question: when black and white civilians behave in the
    same way, are officers more likely to shoot one group than another?

--
- An ideal approach:
.footnote[
<table style="left: 5%; width: 95%">
<col style="width: 5%">
<col style="width: 90%">
  <tr>
