# How was the data analyzed?

- An ideal approach:
  - Clearly articulate the research question
  - Assemble data, theorize about the organizational processes that generated it,    and reason about limitations of that data
.footnote[
<table style="left: 5%; width: 95%">
<col style="width: 5%">
<col style="width: 90%">
  <tr>
    <td align="center"><strong style="">[1]</strong></td>
    <td>Dean Knox and Jonathan Mummolo. 2020. "Making inferences about racial disparities in police violence." <i>PNAS</i>.</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td align="center"><strong style="">[2]</strong></td>
    <td>Bocar Ba, Dean Knox, Jonathan Mummolo, and Roman Rivera. 2021. "The role of officer race and gender in police-civilian interactions in Chicago." <i>Science</i>.</td>
  </tr>
</table>
]

???
- then say, ok, here's the data I have, here's what I can see, here's what I
  can't see
- here's what I can assume about the organizational processes that generated
  the data
- given all that, what's the best-case scenario? is it possible that officers
  are unbiased? what's the worst case?

--
  - Report **range** of possible answers, best- to worst-case

---

# How was the data analyzed?

- An ideal approach:
  - Clearly articulate the research question
  - Assemble data, theorize about the organizational processes that generated it, and reason about limitations of that data
  - Report **range** of possible answers, best- to worst-case
- Prevalent approach in academic/policy policing work:
.footnote[
<table style="left: 5%; width: 95%">
<col style="width: 5%">
<col style="width: 90%">
  <tr>
    <td align="center"><strong style="">[1]</strong></td>
    <td>Dean Knox and Jonathan Mummolo. 2020. "Making inferences about racial disparities in police violence." <i>PNAS</i>.</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td align="center"><strong style="">[2]</strong></td>
    <td>Bocar Ba, Dean Knox, Jonathan Mummolo, and Roman Rivera. 2021. "The role of officer race and gender in police-civilian interactions in Chicago." <i>Science</i>.</td>
  </tr>
</table>
]

???
- this paper is interesting because it doesn't do that
- instead, it exemplifies the standard approach to research in this domain
- which is, find some data that's easy to collect
- pick some model that's easy to use
  - plug the data into the model, get an some stars in your regression, and spin
    a story about police reform
- what this gives you is ONE possible answer to the question that the model is
  asking (which often differs from the question the researcher had in mind),
  under the implicit assumption that you have gold-standard, randomly sampled
  data (assumptions that would be untenable if we actually had to say them out
  loud and really grapple with them)
- I should say that this contrast between abduction & deduction is something
  that comes from Jesper, actually, in the context of the Walmart v Dukes case
  that I'll return to shortly
- what we proved the data and design in this study were fundamentally
  uninformative about the claims that were made
  - if you think critically about this system, there's so much that we can't see
  - the agent could be anti-white, race-neutral, anti-minority
  - anything could be possible: in other words, there's nothing to back up those
    claims

--
  - Assemble data that is reasonably convenient to collect

--
  - Pick an off-the-shelf statistical/ML/AI model to analyze it

--
  - Informally discuss some implications for policing reform

--
  - Report **an** answer
--
 to unstated question
--
 under implicit asms.


