# Bounding the unobserved

- Carefully reason about agent self-reported data
  - Key limitation: principals can't observe stops that aren't made
- **Assumption 1 (all force is reported):** <br>
  &emsp;Force(race, no stop) = 0 for race .small[&in;] {white, min.}
- **Assumption 2 (no anti-white stops):** <br>
  &emsp;Stop(minority) &ge;   Stop(white)
- **Assumption 3 (racial stops are less severe):** <br>
  &emsp;On average, Force(race, decision) is higher<br>
  &emsp;in always-stops than anti-minority stops, for<br>
  &emsp;race .small[&in;] {white, min.} and decision .small[&in;] {stop, no stop}

.footnote[
<table style="left: 5%; width: 95%; font-size: 20px">
<col style="width: 5%">
<col style="width: 90%">
  <tr>
    <td align="center"><strong style="">[1]</strong></td>
    <td>Dean Knox, Will Lowe, and Jonathan Mummolo. 2020. "Administrative records mask racially biased policing." <i>APSR</i>.</td>
  </tr>
  <!-- <tr> -->
  <!--   <td align="center"><strong style="">[2]</strong></td> -->
  <!--   <td>Steven Durlauf and James Heckman. 2020. "An empirical analysis of racial differences in police use of force: A comment." <i>JPE</i>.</td> -->
  <!-- </tr> -->
</table>
]

