<div class="summary">
<br><br><br><br><br>
<h1 style="font-size: 200%; color: black">After 10 weeks of <br>tedious derivations...</h1>
</div>

---

<img src="resources/images/bounds_hands_correct_1.png" style="position: absolute; top: 0%; left: 0%; width: 100%"/>

???
- and this is what you get
- on the left we have Fryer's original estimate, which says about 6% of
  encounters involved discriminatory force, or about 200,000 over a decade of
  NYPD stop-and-frisks
- and what we show is that the only way that could possibly be true is if there
  is zero discrimination in who officers choose to stop
  - in other words, we show that this extremely common form of analysis
    implicitly assumes that there are absolutely no jaywalking-type encounters
  - but it is a bit odd to assume away discrimination in stopping, in a study
    that is trying to estimate how police officers discriminate in use of force
- and depending on how bad that initial stop discrimination is (which we can't
  directly see in this data), the range of possibilities could be much, much worse
- here's that same result with confidence intervals
- it turns out that other studies have looked at stop discrimination in other
  ways, like that "hit rate" analysis I mentioned earlier, and they consistently
  find that at least one third of minority stops are discriminatory
- which implies we're over here: there were at least 400,000 discriminatory uses
  of force, and it could be much worse
--
<img src="resources/images/bounds_hands_correct_2.png" style="position: absolute; top: 0%; left: 0%; width: 100%"/>
--
<img src="resources/images/bounds_hands_correct_3.png" style="position: absolute; top: 0%; left: 0%; width: 100%"/>
--
<img src="resources/images/bounds_hands_correct_4.png" style="position: absolute; top: 0%; left: 0%; width: 100%"/>
--
<img src="resources/images/bounds_hands_correct_5.png" style="position: absolute; top: 0%; left: 0%; width: 100%"/>

---

<img src="resources/images/bounds_other_correct.png" style="position: absolute; top: 0%; left: 0%; width: 100%"/>

???
- that was for officers laying hands on a civilian, but we can repeat this
  exercise for other levels of force, like putting someone on the ground or
  striking them with a baton
- and across the board, the takeaway is the same
- in many cases, the standard approach would seem to show no discrimination
- but that's because it's naively taking the police data at face value, rather
  than thinking about blind spots in agent self-reports
- when you actually account for the fact that the minority data is diluted by a
  huge number of jaywalking-type encounters, you immediately see that the true
  severity of the problem is far larger than it originally appeared
- now, I've worked quite closely with the ACLU legal analytics team, and they
  tell me that the methods we developed in this paper are now standard practice
  in their discrimination cases

<!-- -- -->

<!-- <img src="resources/images/bounds_gfk_correct.png" style="position: absolute; top: 0%; left: 0%; width: 100%"/> -->

---

# Minimax org. design

- **Goal:** constrain worst-case agent deviation

--
  - Bounds show obs. indistinguishable agent behavior
  - Highest point of this region represents the worst case

--
- Shape of a squad's bounds are governed by:
  - **Width:** amount of discretion to initiate stops
  - **Slope:** total amount of force used by the squad
  - **Intercept:** racial diff. in use-of-force rates, ignoring whether stop
    should have been made in the first place
--
- Reforms can be designed to constrain these factors, but the set of feasible
  reforms depends on context
  
---

<img src="resources/images/klm_units.png" style="position: absolute; top: 0%; left: 0%; width: 100%"/>

???
- as a concrete example, think about two kinds of units: plainclothes and
  uniformed squads
- in NYPD, plainclothes officers use slightly more force, so the red slope is
  a little bit higher
- and plainclothes officers have greater observed disparities, so the intercept
  is higher
- how can we redesign their work to reduce the blue and red peaks?
- for uniformed officers, we can limit discretion in stopping: tighten the rules
  of engagement, so this blue region doesn't extend as far to the right
- but that reform doesn't make sense for plainclothes officers: the whole point
  of those squads is blend in, they have to adapt to the situation and exercise
  discretion
- so what else can we do? well, we can target the slope: limit the amount of
  force they use. plainclothes officers are best for surveillance and informant
  work, they shouldn't need to use force
  - we can enforce that with a policy that says, if you do use force, you're put
    on desk duty for a week while internal affairs investigates
  - do it too many times, and you're put back on uniformed patrol

---

<img src="resources/images/klm_tasks.png" style="position: absolute; top: 0%; left: 0%; width: 100%"/>

???
- we can use the same ideas to reason about task allocation
- let's talk about
  - low-discretion stops like violent crime
  - high-discretion stops like "furtive movement"
  - and everything else in the middle
- so this is kind of the reverse situation:
  - the nature of dealing with violent crime is you often need to use force
  - we can't intervene on that, so the next best option is to take that task and
    give it to dedicated SWAT-type units who just respond to calls
  - don't let heavily armed officers just roam the streets with discretion to
    stop whoever they want
- we could imagine a different reform for these really questionable stops like
  "furtive movement" and "suspicious bulge": increase accountability to peers
  and leaders by hiring more minority officers
  - that's a reform that we can conceptualize as reducing the intercept, the
    slope, AND the horizontal width

---

class: center, middle, inverse

# How can we extend this
# approach to other agencies
# and data environments?

???
- what we've talked about so far are two specific monitoring tasks
  - when you have data on officer-involved shootings or stops, respectively
- but there are 18,000 law enforcement agencies in america
  - each of them potentially recording different combinations of data
  - and if we have to sit down to derive bounds on terms of agent behavior for
    each one, that's just not feasible
- so now I'm going to talk about how we built an algorithm to automate this
  best-/worst-case reasoning
  


---

<img src="./resources/images/intro_dag_full.png" style="position: absolute; left: 2.5%; top: 12.5%; width: 100%; z-index: ;"/>
---
<img src="./resources/images/mbs_context.png" id="slidedownright" style="position: absolute; left: 2.5%; top: 12.5%; width: 100%; z-index: ;"/>
???
- I'll introduce these ideas through the lens of a recent court victory on
  traffic discrimination
- where we helped the aclu show that the kansas highway patrol was
  discriminating in traffic enforcement 
  - they were stopping one group more, compared to another group driving the
    same speed in the same times and places
  
---

