<!-- # Ideal encounter types -->

<!-- - "Principal stratification" of each variable -->

<!-- -- -->
<!-- - Two driver types: -->

<!-- -- -->
<!--   - Minority drivers -->
<!--   - White drivers -->

<!-- -- -->
<!-- - Four stops types (or officer types): -->

<!-- -- -->
<!--   - Always stop -->
<!--   - Anti-minority stop -->
<!--   - Anti-white stop -->
<!--   - Never stop -->
  
<!-- --- -->

<!-- # Ideal encounter types -->

<!-- - "Principal stratification" of each variable -->
<!-- - Two driver types: -->
<!--   - Minority drivers -->
<!--   - White drivers -->
<!-- - Four stops types (or officer types): -->
<!--   - Always stop -->
<!--   - Anti-minority stop -->
<!--   - <s>Anti-white stop</s> -->
<!--   - Never stop -->
<!-- --- -->
# Hypothetical states of world
<img src="./resources/images/3d_base.png" style="position: absolute; left: -5%; top: 20%; height: 80%; z-index: ;"/>
???
- now we can geometrically represent the possible states of the world
- each point in this cube is one possible world
  - or one way that drivers are behaving and agents are reacting
- the height of that point is the proportion of minority drivers
  - so if, hypothetically we were up at the top, that means every driver on the
    road is a minority
  - and the proportion of white drivers is just 1 minus that
---
<!-- <p style="position: absolute; left: 9%; top: 3%; width: 40%; z-index: 2;"> -->
<!--   <b>Assumption:</b> -->
<!-- </p> -->
<!-- <p style="position: absolute; left: 45%; top: 5.5%; width: 40%; z-index: 2; font-size: 100%"> -->
<!--   Pr( anti-white stop ) = 0 -->
<!-- </p> -->
<!-- <p style="position: absolute; left: 9%; top: 8%; width: 40%; z-index: 2;"> -->
<!--   <b>Laws of probability:</b> -->
<!-- </p> -->
<!-- <p style="position: absolute; left: 45%; top: 10.25%; width: 50%; z-index: 2; font-size: 100%"> -->
<!--   Pr(always) + Pr(anti-minority) + Pr(never) = 1 -->
<!-- </p> -->
<!-- <img src="./resources/images/3d_lawprob.png" style="position: absolute; left: -5%; top: 20%; height: 80%; z-index: ;"/> -->
<!-- ??? -->
<!-- - now, we can take stock of what we know -->
<!-- - we know that if you think about the officer types -->
<!--   - those also have to add up to 1 -->
<!--   - here I'm just showing always stops and discriminatory stops on the bottom -->
<!--     axes, because whatever is left over must be the number of never stops -->
<!-- - and we know that you can't have, for example, 90% always stops and 90% -->
<!--   discriminatory stops -->
<!--   - because that'd add up to more than 100%, which doesn't make sense -->
<!--   - so already we know that we have to be somewhere in this back half -->
<!-- --- -->

**Observed stop margin:**<br>
Pr( stop )
<p style="position: absolute; left: 50%; top: 5.5%;  z-index: 2; font-size: 100%;">
  Pr( min. ) Pr( anti-min. stop )
  <br> &emsp;+ Pr( min. ) Pr( always stop )
  <br> &emsp;&ensp;&emsp; + [ 1 - Pr( min. ) ] Pr( always stop )
</p>
<img src="./resources/images/3d_stopmargin.png" style="position: absolute; left: -5%; top: 20%; height: 80%; z-index: ;"/>

???
- now we can start pulling in the traffic-sensor data
- we know that 25% of cars are stopped, which narrows down the possibilities
- we can backward induct: how does a stop occur?
  - it could be that a minority driver met an anti-minority officer
  - or, it could be that they met an always-stop officer
  - or a white person met that always-stop officer
- what this is saying is that, even though we can't directly see what's going on
  out there on the highway, we can indirectly reason about it
  - the unobserved reality has to be somewhere on this surface
- the fact that only 25% of cars are stopped helps rule out a lot of options
  - like, obviously it can't be that there 100% always-stops, because that
    wouldn't add up
---

**Observed stop records:**<br>
Pr( minority | stop )

<p style="position: absolute; left: 47.5%; top: 5.5%;  z-index: 2; font-size: 100%;">
  <u>&emsp;Pr( min. ) Pr( anti-min. stop OR always stop )&emsp;</u>
  <br> [ Pr( min. ) Pr( anti-min. stop) + Pr( always stop ) ]
</p>
<img src="./resources/images/3d_stoprecords.png" style="position: absolute; left: -5%; top: 20%; height: 80%; z-index: ;"/>
???
- and we can do the same with our police stop records
- we know that 75% of stopped cars had minority drivers
- again, backward inducting: what does that tell us about the possible states of
  the world?
- it says the unobserved world has to be somewhere on **this** surface, too
- for example it can't be that every driver is white, because that would
  contradict the fact that we have all these minority stops
---

**Remaining range of possible agent behavior:**<br>
<img src="./resources/images/3d_feasible.png" style="position: absolute; left: -5%; top: 20%; height: 80%; z-index: ;"/>
???
- so now, combining traffic sensors and police records, we've narrowed down the
  possibilities
- and after triangulating all of this information, we can ask:
  - given what we know, and what we've been able to rule out
  - among all the possible worlds that remain
- what's the best-case scenario for agent behavior? 
  - is it possible that they're not discriminating?
  - or can we rule race-neutral behavior with this incomplete information?
---

**External benchmarking:**<br>
<!-- External reference for Pr( minority ) -->
<p style="position: absolute; left: 60%; top: 5.5%;  z-index: 2; font-size: 100%;">
  &alpha;&ensp;&le;&ensp;Pr( min. )&ensp;&le;&ensp;&beta;<br>
</p>
<img src="./resources/images/3d_benchmark.png" style="position: absolute; left: -5%; top: 20%; height: 80%; z-index: ;"/>

???
- and we can bring in even more information
- we have mobile-phone data that says, when you look at gas stations along the
  highway
- say, 40% of customers are minorities
  - of course that doesn't mean that exactly 40% of police encounters are with
    minorities
  - but it's unlikely that police are seeing less than 20% minorities, or more
    than 60%
  - in other words, the unobserved world has to be somewhere in this range

---

class: gray

.large[<br><br>**Proposition 1** (informal)<br>
Any discrete causal graph can be reparameterized in terms of a finite number of generalized principal strata w.l.o.g. for the full joint distr. of potential outcomes.]
<br>

???
- we have a bunch of theoretical results that, at the end of the day, prove this is possible for any discrete system
- for any monitoring question you want to ask
- any theory or assumptions you can bring to bear
- and any dataset or datasets you might have, no matter how incomplete they may be
- you can engage in this kind of reasoning

--
.large[**Proposition 2** (informal)<br>
The probability of any factual or counterfactual event is a polynomial in variables that represent generalized principal strata sizes.]
<br>

--
.large[**Corollary 1** (informal)<br>
Any elementary arithmetic functional of the joint distr. of potential outcomes can be reparameterized as a polynomial fraction in strata sizes. Any polynomial fraction can be transformed into a system of polynomials in an expanded variable space.]
<br>

--
.large[**Theorem 1** (informal)<br>
Minimization and maximization of a polynomialized estimand subject to polynomialized constraints representing empirical evidence (and optional modeling assumptions) produces sharp causal bounds.
]

--
<div class="summary" style="position: absolute; top:0%; height: 87.5%;">
<br><br>
<h1 style="font-size: 190%; color: black">Any agent monitoring task<br>in a discrete system can be<br>reformulated in terms of<br>equivalent computational<br>optimization problems</h1>
</div>

