# Other ongoing work

???
1. having now worked on a number of doj investigations, something that stands
   out is the amount of qualitative review that lawyers do
  - in terms of case review, watching bodycam video, and so on
  - there's just no replacement for getting your hands dirty in the raw data
  - what we realized was that there were huge inefficiencies in the process
  - and that we could use an extension the quantitative analysis I just
    presented to help with case selection for the qualitative analysis
  - to efficiently target cases that can narrow down (in that investigation)
    possible agent behavior toward mentally ill people
  <!-- - if you're worried about officers misrepresenting civilian behavior,
  then we --> <!-- should be specifically hunting down those "resisting arrest"
  and "suspicious --> <!-- behavior" cases and studying those -->
1. the second project looks at bodycam video from a different angle
   - these videos are interesting because they're such a waste of
     resources. agencies pay insane amounts of money to store terabytes of
     footage, but police chiefs tell us hardly anyone watches it because
     it's too much work
   - we're using computer-vision and speech-analysis to summarize videos so a
     sergeant can get an automatic weekly update that they can skim

--
1. Efficient allocation of monitoring resources
  - Verifying agent-reported data with bodycam review is costly

--
  - Techniques for efficiently allocating principal's data-collection
    resources (identify videos that help narrow bounds fastest)
--
1. Computational methods for early intervention
  - Computer-vision & speech analysis of bodycam videos

--
1. Descriptive representation in police bureaucracies
  - Largest public registry of officers, 99 of top 100 agencies

???
- a third project is looking at this idea of descriptive representation
  - that you can get better performance from a bureaucracy by staffing it with
    people who are like the customers and can understand them
  - we've collected what's now the largest registry of officers nationwide,
    covering more than a third of local law enforcement and 99 of the 100 largest
    agencies
  - we quantify how much local police diverge from local residents on race,
    gender, age, income, political orientation
  - and show why that matters in terms of enforcement decisions
- and a fourth project I mentioned briefly at the start
  - looking at how civilian oversight is structured nationwide
  - getting incredibly detailed process data on how misconduct is investigated
    and how officers almost never get serious discipline for it
  - we find showing this data to local residents makes them trust police less
    and want to cooperate less
  - but you can counteract that somewhat with greater transparency
  - walking residents through the process in detail (here's what officers are
    accused of, here's what was done to investigate, here's the evidence, etc)

--
1. Management of police misconduct investigations
  - National census of oversight organizations

--
  - Process data on findings & discipline (Chicago, NYC, Phila.)

--
  - Weak transparency undermines civilian trust & willingness<br> to cooperate, but strong transparency improves it

