name: chicago_extra

# How can we do better?

- Three years of open-records requests
  - Chicago Police Dept. & Dept. of Human Resources
  - Denials overturned by Illinois Attorney General on appeal

.footnote[
<table style="left: 5%; width: 95%">
<col style="width: 5%">
<col style="width: 90%">
  <!-- <tr> -->
  <!--   <td align="center"><strong style="">[1]</strong></td> -->
  <!--   <td>Dean Knox and Jonathan Mummolo. 2020. "Making inferences about racial disparities in police violence." <i>PNAS</i>.</td> -->
  <!-- </tr> -->
  <tr>
    <td align="center"><strong style="">[1]</strong></td>
    <td>Bocar Ba, Dean Knox, Jonathan Mummolo, and Roman Rivera. 2021. "The role of officer race and gender in police-civilian interactions in Chicago." <i>Science</i>.</td>
  </tr>
</table>
]

???
- how would you tackle this in earnest?
  - i'll come back to claim #1 (racial bias) in a second
  - and for now focus on claim #2 (diversifying police)
- it took my team three years of foia requests to get enough data to do a
  careful, causally identified analysis of police diversification
- who officers were, what actions they took, when and where they showed up to
  work every day
- those shift records are key, because they let us see when different kinds
  officers get assigned to do the same tasks and face the same kinds of
  civilian behavior
  - that lets us ask, why is it one officer can do their job without resorting
    to violence, while another seems to use force a lot?
- what we found was that actually, having a diverse police force matters a lot
  - officers who are minority or female tend to engage in less enforcement
  - but it's not that they're just pulling back: there's almost no difference in
    how they handle violent crime
  - instead, it's that these officers make fewer minor drug arrests, and
    stopping people for questionable things like "loitering" or "suspicious
    behavior" less
  - and it turns out that means fewer black residents get caught up in this
    low-level discretionary enforcement

--
- Data covering ~7,000 officers; 
--
~1.6 million stops, arrests, uses of force; 
--
~2.9 million shift assignments

--
- Use of shift records is crucial:
  - Identifies officers assigned to face common circumstances
  - Accounts for days when officers choose to take no action

--
- When facing the same pool of civ. behavior:
  - Minority & female officers enforce less severely
  - Effects largest for minority civs. and minor offenses


